  https://i.ytimg.com/vi/ELUl-cAtUIE/hq720.jpg

## Nice to haves (do not implement)

### True 3D heightmap-based world with 3-axis movement and rotation freedom

Heighmap is a 2D matrix, every point's value represents its elevation. 4 adjacent points represent vertices for 2
triangles. Lets have another 2D matrix that specifies the orientation of the 2 triangles (either split the rectangle
area / way or \ way). This triangle orientation matrix has the dimensions of the elevation matrix minus one row and
column.

Use x and y axes to navigate the matrix, and z axis for elevation. Lets use painter's algorithm for simplicity. To do
roll (rotation around y axis), calculate the normalized on-screen vector perpendicular to the horizon. To do pitch
(rotation around x axis), calculate where along the roll-determined vector the horizon will be on screen with the
vector passing through the center of the screen. To do yaw (rotation around z axis), calculate the normalized vector
pointing "forward" within the heightmap.

To render:
1. Use the vectors and positions to determine the square at the center of the render-horizon by adding the product of
   render distance and z-orienation vector to the camera's position.
2. Use a vector perpendicular to z-orientation vector to navigate the adjacent squares and render the horizon, stopping
   as soon as a square to render would be off-screen completely. Keep track of the number of squares rendered towards
   left and towards right.
3. Step towards the camera using the negated z-orientation vector.
4. Repeat from step 2. using the previous known on-screen squares count (update the count afterwards, it can increase
   as well!) until reaching the camera, or all of the squares within the tested range are off-screen.

This effectively does the rotations from scene to frustrum for us by navigating the heightmap using pre-rotated
vectors.

To render a square, use the fact that all sides of every square is the same distance, and use the pre-computed vectors
to efectively do the rotations from scene to frustrum:
1. To get vertices of a square, use the floating-point position within the square pointing to the square to render, get
   the within-square [0, 1] x,y coordinates.
2. Use the square side length, within-square coordinates and z-orientation vector to calculate x,y coordinates within
   frustrum z is vertex's z - camera's z.
   xf = l * (xr * v.x - yr * v.y) + frustrum_square.x
   yf = l * (xr * v.y + yr * v.x) + frustrum_square.y
   Note: checThese are the rotation equations. Note that v.x si cosinus, v.y is sinus. See
   http://fastgraph.com/makegames/3drotation/
3. Use the in-frustrum coordinates to calculate on-screen projection, round the results to whole numbers to prevent
   stitching issues.
4. Render the triangles using the on-screen coordinates, unless the edge closest to the camera's position is farther
   (regarding the horizon->close ground orientation) than the farthest edge - back-face culling.

### UV texture mapping approximation

Use clipping paths and strething the image as needed. Note that this does not take care of rotation, so the use of this
is limited to surface that do not rotate on the screen around the axis pointing towards the camera.

### Render distance & frustrum culling

Add `Camera.renderDistance: number` - specifies a sphere surrounding the camera, everything outside it will not be
rendered.

Add `GameObject.sizeRadius: number` - radius of the smallest sphere centered on object's position containing the
object's mesh and the meshes of all its sub-objects (can be implemented in `AbstractGameObject` as a getter).

Add `GameObject.meshSizeRadius: number` - radius of the smallest sphere centered on object's position containing the
object's mesh, without its sub-objects. Declared in `GameObject`, implemented in `AbstractGameObject` as `0` (every game
object must implement it on its own if it wants to utilize it).

Add `GameObject.getMeshSizeRadius(mesh: Mesh): number` - returns the radius of the smallest sphere centered on [0, 0, 0]
containing the provided mesh.

Changes to renderer(s):
- first filter the game objects to render to create a linear list of objects to render from the forest of objects in the
  scene
  - for each object: calculate the object's distance from the camera. Add the object to the render list only if the
    distance is lower or equal to `camera.renderDistance + gameObject.sizeRadius`
- render the objects in the created linear list

### Depth-based object culling

This is insipired by z-buffer, but works on game object level.

After doing other culls of game objects to render by the renderer, apply the following filtering:
- objectsToFilter = [...(so-far filtered game objets)]
- objectsToRender = []
- for object of objectsToFilter
  - onScreenPosition = camera.project(object.absolutePosition)
  - boudingCircleVector = camera.getVectorTo(object).getRightAngleVector().normalize().multiply(object.sizeRadius)
  - boundingCirclePoint = camera.project(object.absolutePosition.add(boudingCircleVector))
  - onScreenRadius = distance(onScreenPosition, boundingCirclePoint)
  - cameraDistance = distance(camera.position, object.position)
  - shouldEnqueue = true
  - for enqueuedObjectDetails of objectsToRender
    - if (
        cameraDistance > enqueuedObjectDetails.cameraDistance &&
        distance(object.absolutePosition, enqueuedObjectDetails.gameObject.absolutePosition) <= enqueuedObjectDetails.onScreenRadius - onScreenRadius
      )
      - shouldEnqueue = false
      - break
    - if (
        cameraDistance < enqueuedObjectDetails.cameraDistance &&
        distance(object.absolutePosition, enqueuedObjectDetails.gameObject.absolutePosition) <= onScreenRadius - enqueuedObjectDetails.onScreenRadius
      )
      objectsToRender.delete(enqueuedObjectDetails)
  - if shouldEnqueue
    - objectsToRender.push({gameObject: object, onScreenRadius, cameraDistance})

Render only the game object that are in `objectsToRender` array.

### Culling of objects not faced by camera

Check the angle between camera's direction and the point on circle representing game object's sizeRadius sphere from
camera's perspective that's closes to the vector representing camera's direction. If the angle is greater than angle to
the corner of the viewport, cull the object from the render list.

### UV mapovanie textúr na trojuholník

Trhovník má vrcholy A, B a C
Vrcholy sú mapované na textúru na UV súradnice U, V a W odpovedajúce vrcholom A, B a C
Mapovanie prebieha až po premietnutí do 2D súradníc na obrazovke, pixel po pixeli.
Mapovanie bodu X v trojuholníku na texel:
V1 = Vector(A, B)
V2 = Vector(A, C)
Vx = Vector(A, X)
AngleV1V2 = V1.angleTo(V2)
AngleV1Vx = V1.angleTo(Vx)
AngleRatio = AngleV1Vx / AngleV1V2
EdgeProjection = Vector.lerp(B, C, AngleRatio)
DistanceRatio = Vx.magnitude / Vector(A, EdgeProjection).magnitude
TEdgeProjection = Vector.lerp(V, W, AngleRatio)
TexelVector = Vector(U, TEdgeProjection) * DistanceRatio
TexelCoordinates = U + TexelVector

Alternatívny (presnejší?) postup:
použiť 2D barycentric coordinate system - viď
https://www.scratchapixel.com/lessons/3d-basic-rendering/ray-tracing-rendering-a-triangle/barycentric-coordinates

Veľkosť / normalizácia vektoru vyžaduje odmocninu. To by sa dalo možno optimalizovať pomocou tohto algoritmu (záleží či
JS engine používa SSE inštrukcie): https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_inverse_square_root
V prípade normalizácie je možné použiť rovno násobenie výsledkom, keďže vypočíta *obrátenú* odmocninu.
